\par                                        The Three Sisters and Kin
\par 
\par         Food is often a popular subject. These stories will tell how our
\par 
\par  world came to have the wonderful plant/food contributions from North 
\par 
\par America, South America, and Mesoamerica in the late 1500\rquote s.  Before that 
\par 
\par time, the Italian cuisine had no tomatoes, The Irish and Russians had  no
\par 
\par potatoes, and the Thai and others, had no chiles.
\par 
\par         When Cortez and Pizzaro came into South and Mesoamerica, they 
\par 
\par pillaged  treasures of gold and silver. But they, and Columbus, also returned
\par 
\par   to the Old World with even greater treasures in food and plants. One 
\par 
\par example, early hunters and gatherers had found a plant with a one inch tasty
\par 
\par  bit\emdash later they planted them, cared for them, saved next year\rquote s seed from
\par 
\par  only the best ears, and hybridized them, and mais-or corn- became a staple
\par 
\par  for the early peoples.  When mais was taken to the Old World, the ear had 
\par 
\par been improved to produce a five or six inch product. Improvements 
\par 
\par continued around the world and today, we may buy ears 14  or 15 inches
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par  long.
\par 
\par        Early Americans were grinding corn and making flat breads, using
\par 
\par  kernals for hominy (boiled in the ashes of the fire) and popping. Today the
\par 
\par grain  is the third most used  crop in the world. Corn grows a tall and  strong 
\par 
\par stalk,  beans (green and lima and kidney and others) wrap themselves 
\par 
\par around, and climb the stalk.  Squash, with  it\rquote s large leaves stays low on the
\par 
\par  ground and reaches out, shading the root area of all three and retaining the 
\par 
\par sometimes scarce water. The variety attracts helpful insects and the trio of 
\par 
\par plants use different nutrients from the soil they share.  These are the \'93Three
\par 
\par Sisters\'94 of the early planters.- Corn, Beans, and Squash\emdash all taken back to
\par 
\par  Europe by early sailing ships.\emdash treasures shared with the  world and still
\par 
\par  giving. 
\par 
\par            If you have never had  cooked squash blossom, watch for it in the 
\par 
\par fusion cooking we find  today. It is a delicate and delicious treat, and in the 
\par 
\par new  National Museum of  the American Indian (an adjunct of the 
\par 
\par Smithsonian), squash blossom foods are served seasonally, in their 
\par 
\par restaurants, named }{\f1\fs28\insrsid11360528 Mitsitam\emdash }{\f1\insrsid11360528 a word}{\f1\fs28\insrsid11360528  }{\fs28\insrsid11360528 derived from a Piscataway and 
\par 
\par Delaware Indians meaning \'93Let\rquote s Eat.\'94 Recently, FOHP Board member,
\par 
\par  Joei Bidwell and I had stuffed squash blossoms at  the Campanile on La
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par  Cienega in Los Angeles, a much loved, Mediterranean restaurant in an 
\par 
\par historic old building shared by the La Brea Bakery. What a treat!
\par 
\par       Potatoes from the Inca in the Andes were another new gift to the old
\par 
\par  world in the mid 1500\rquote s. Today, there are over two hundred and fifty
\par 
\par varieties, all from early planters\rquote  high Andes and MesoAmerican 
\par 
\par gardens. The Inca were brilliant botanists who cultivated wild plants with
\par 
\par  great success, including an astounding three thousand varieties of  potato in
\par 
\par  a rainbow of color and sizes. In the high Andes, woman\rquote s job, after
\par 
\par  growing, digging up and putting potatoes on the high Andes plateau near
\par 
\par  the home, was to walk on the potatoes \endash frozen through the night by the cold
\par 
\par  and  thawing through the day by the sun\emdash as they thawed, the women
\par 
\par  squeezed the water out with their feet. Freeze, thaw  and squeeze.  This 
\par 
\par process continued until the water content was low enough for safe storage. It 
\par 
\par was called \'93chuno\'94 and is an important part of the South American diet
\par 
\par  today still.  The potato, a new treasure, and the freeze-dry process was
\par 
\par known and used many centuries ago. Incredibly, the Inca and Aztec had 
\par 
\par over two thousand varieties; today over two hundred varieties are in use.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par      Potato chips\emdash a picnic, party, deli and gametime favorite\emdash came later
\par 
\par in Florida when a Native American was the proud chef in a diner.
\par 
\par A man entered with a small party in the early 1900\rquote s.  He ordered fried 
\par 
\par potatoes\emdash and included in the order a message to the chef,
\par 
\par \'93Cut }{\fs32\insrsid11360528 very }{\fs28\insrsid11360528 thin.\'94 }{\insrsid11360528 The cook decided to outdo his customer, shaving the
\par 
\par vegetable, instead of the expected  complaints, there were happy diners\emdash and 
\par 
\par the special potatoes became potato chips, a drawing card to the diner!.
\par 
\par      Once when my husband, Gene, and I were traveling in Sri Lanka, we went
\par 
\par  through  an orchid farm. The orchids were beautiful, but the older man who 
\par 
\par was the manager outshown the flowers with his knowledge of them. One
\par 
\par  story he told us, with apologies that he had no more reprints to give me of 
\par 
\par his work  that had gone into a very erudite magazine, was of the black slave
\par 
\par who had for many years lived on an island in the Caribbean, gone into the
\par 
\par  rainforest where the vanda orchid grew and picked seed  pods for shipping
\par 
\par  to customers around the world to use for their aroma and flavor. On his 
\par 
\par own, he had been  experimenting with an idea he had. He took his idea to
\par 
\par  the company  manager,  who liked it so much that he gave the man: his
\par 
\par  freedom, one hundred dollars, and a boat ride to Florida.  In Florida, 
\par 
\par alone,  knowing nothing about the area, he found a friendly inn and spent
\par 
\par  some money. Unfortunately, he got drunk, and was picked up and jailed for
\par 
\par  drunkeness.  When he got out, he immediately found a ride back to the
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par  island where he had worked  and asked to be allowed to do the same job but
\par 
\par  as a free man, with pay. And there he worked \endash  picking pods of the vanda
\par 
\par orchid and shipping them to customers around the world. Perhaps he also 
\par 
\par worked to soak them in alcohol, water, and sugar to create Vanilla-- his own
\par 
\par  discovery , so delicious in flavor and exotic in aroma. Vanda  orchid
\par 
\par pods had been used by native peoples for hundreds of years. They were trade
\par 
\par goods and  taken by ocean-going canoes to other peoples. 
\par 
\par            Another time, Gene and I were in Cancun, Mexico, on the small beach next to our 
\par 
\par hotel,  there was an ancient stone construction\emdash where signal fires had been lighted by 
\par 
\par Maya and Aztec traders to guide the trading canoes on their way. Thus, the next time 
\par 
\par you use that  handy little vanilla extract bottle you may appreciate the source and enjoy it 
\par 
\par even more. Perhaps the same man, in 1841, a clever freed slave named Edmond Albius 
\par 
\par invented a technique for pollinating  vanilla which made it possible to mass-produce
\par 
\par one of the  most labor intensive agricultural product in the world today\emdash one
\par 
\par vanilla bean, can sell for between two to three dollars.
\par 
\par        Another contribution and one very important to the Maya, and later the 
\par 
\par  Aztec, was chocolate. The cacao bean was used as money. Not only a trade item, the 
\par 
\par bean was important in religious rituals and social relationships. It was used as a bitter 
\par 
\par drink often with a dash of chile, and sometimes  ground corn or honey,  made frothy 
\par 
\par by pouring rapidly back and forth between two cups before serving. 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par           Legend has it that the cacao seeds had been brought from Paradise and
\par 
\par  that  they  provided  wisdom and power to the partaker. On Christopher
\par 
\par  Colombus\rquote  fourth visit to the Americas, he returned to Spain with the cacao
\par 
\par bean where for nearly a century, the Spanish monarchy and monasteries kept the
\par 
\par cacao bean a secret for use and trade. They also planted  cacao trees in their 
\par 
\par overseas colonies, enjoying a lucrative monopoly until  an Italian traveler stole the
\par 
\par secret and took it to other European cities. Today Brazil and the Ivory Coast  provide
\par 
\par nearly one-half of the world\rquote s chocolate, but the United States leads the world in cacao
\par 
\par bean importation and chocolate  production.
\par 
