\par            }{\fs28\insrsid11360528  Tapioca, a root starch derived from the cassava  (manioc) plant,
\par 
\par native to South America and the Maya, who learned to use it for food, 
\par 
\par were clever enough to  remove the cyanide within the root.  They even had a
\par 
\par  use for the cyanide, too, coating their arrow tips to enhance hunting success!
\par 
\par Today,  the cassava root is used in South America and West Indies for food, 
\par 
\par though not always successfully. Sadly, while Gene and I were in Egypt 
\par 
\par  recently, there was on CNN a report of some forty-seven children who died 
\par 
\par  of improperly prepared cassava at a school in the West Indies Happily, our 
\par 
\par little box of Minute Tapioca comes to us well processed.
\par 
\par .     Today, in Indonesia, the cassava roots make raw materials for crackers, 
\par }{\insrsid11360528 
\par toothpaste, paper, and even textiles. In South America, and MesoAmerica it 
\par 
\par is also used for \'93chicha\'94\emdash an alcoholic drink. The drug industry is using 
\par 
\par tapioca in drugs, also. I am trying to find out just how it is used\emdash for the gel 
\par 
\par  capsules? For time release? With each new revelation, I find new questions.
\par 
\par        Another Native American \'93contribution\'94 to the world is tobacco.  
\par 
\par  The Indians used it for rituals and on special occasions.  Today it 
\par 
\par is Big Business.  Also, chicle, the gum that people chew and often throw on
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par  the street and sidewalks for the unwary to step in.
\par 
\par            Lobster\emdash a high priced gourmet item today, was food for the
\par 
\par  Narraganset tribe of north-eastern United States, who used lobster traps over two 
\par 
\par thousand years ago.  Interestingly, the traps used by Baltimore  and Boston lobstermen 
\par 
\par today are almost identical in size and shape. The first settlers however from Europe 
\par 
\par evidentally were  not into lobster. In Baltimore, Benjamin Franklin loved to go fishing
\par 
\par  and on a  warm day he would sit on rock or  pier and dangle his feet in the cool water. 
\par 
\par He said that fishing is a perfect thing to do\emdash if it were not for the BUGS (lobster) that
\par 
\par  keep bothering his feet!  Then, about the same time the good City Fathers ,
\par 
\par searching for a way to save money,  (sound like our City Fathers  today?) 
\par 
\par thought: \'93All those lobsters and nothing to do with them!\'94  On the other 
\par 
\par hand, there were prisoners in the local prison who had to be fed at taxpayers\rquote 
\par 
\par  expense.  Solution?  \'93Feed those prisoners on lobster two or three times a week.\'94  It was
\par 
\par  not long before the prisoners began protesting strongly about their lobster diet. The City
\par 
\par  Fathers had to rethink their plan.
\par 
